&gt; null.

Why is this happening?
Well, your `Comment` class doesn&#39;t define `userId`, `projectId`, `parentCommentId` properties.

That&#39;s the expected behavior of the deserializer. If you don&#39;t want to manually create a object (i.e.: using DTOs), you have to tell the deserializer to create a instance of the `RegisteredUser`, `Project` and `Comment` (for the parentComment).

To do that, you would simply create the object in your JSON.

Instead of this:

    {
        &quot;comment&quot;: &quot;third comment&quot;,
        &quot;userId&quot;: 2, 
        &quot;projectId&quot; : 3,
        &quot;parentCommentId&quot; : 2
    }

Try this

    {
        &quot;comment&quot;: &quot;Foo bar&quot;,
        &quot;projectId&quot;: {
            &quot;projectId&quot;: 3
        },
        &quot;user&quot;: {
            &quot;userId&quot;: 1
        },
        &quot;parentCommentId&quot;: {
            &quot;commentId&quot;: 2
        }
    }

This works, but is much more verbose than the way you&#39;re trying to insert. That&#39;s one of the reasons I always use DTOs for request / response objects.

